text: This trailer gives the viewer no clear idea what's going on.  He's driving around a cornfield looking at an "Indian surveillance drone" and then says "solar sails will power an entire farm."  Huh?  Then there's fire and dust in the cornfields and someone says they've run out of food.  Yet there are all these shots of healthy-looking cornfields before and after.  Then, having been a pilot (with no apparent experience as an astronaut), he's the man to fly on a spaceship whose mission will somehow save the Earth from this unexplained doom.  I'm sure the film will make more sense, but this trailer is perplexing.

text: I had been anticipating this trailer for such a long time, and it was a partial reason why I went to see Godzilla last night, so I could see the new trailer on the big screen. As soon as McConaughey popped up, I yelled "shhhh" in the buzzing theater and everything went quiet. I stopped eating my popcorn, and a beautiful two minutes ensued... This movie is going to be the best of 2014, I can feel it. It has so much going for it. Nolan's craft and perfection with his movies is like no one else's; his unique style will be breathtaking. (He's already warned theaters that the sound design and output will be like nothing else before.) I can Interstellar winning 10 Oscars next February including a second consecutive Best Actor for MM. I will be in Boston at the time of this release and I hope to attend a big midnight premiere! I won't be sleeping much come October! The excitement is here!

text: To everyone that believes we aren't meant to live in space: Of course humanity isn't meant to live in space, the billions of years of evolution into our species happened all on this planet. However, through research, we've discovered other habitable planets throughout our own galaxy. Our galaxy is upon billions of other galaxies with potentially habitable planets. Science shows that Earth will eventually run out of the resources we have come to depend on to sustain life. So what do you do? Sit here and do nothing, telling yourself that we're meant to die out in a few thousand years or less? Or do you grasp your intelligence and realize that we are in control of our future?﻿

Some of us thank god/s when we find our lost House Key but forget that 8 million kids under five years of age die every single year from horrific diseases and they won't be thanking God/Allah/Zeus or Mickey Mouse. This is a film but the warnings are there. Soon there will be no other species left due to our greed, population growth and ignorance. We will hunt Animals, eat them and destroy their habitat. Then all that will remain is tens of Billons of people, all wanting more and what each other has and Wars will follow. The writing is one the wall, we are fucked. And yet we could be so much more. Science, education, investigation, compassion, empathy and reason could still win the day? Wake up. We need to change before we all loose.

text: Funny with all these global warming apocalyptic movies, in which mankind wants to leave Earth in search of a new home... #1) We are accepting that we are ruining Earth, yet we don't do anything to fix it (and I mean, now, today, in the real Earth right here). We make the mess, then we want to leave to #2: make the exact same mess in a new world. Accept it. The human being will always be greedy, voracious, careless, selfish, no matter where it goes. We have it in our genes. The first thing that we'll do in another planet is look for gold, then pick the best place, make frontiers, and prohibit anybody else from getting to those resources. Humanity has no unity because we can't share, we want it all, and we'll always consider ourselves worthier and better that the others.

text: This isn't about wormhole's or blackhole's the spaceship in the video seems to use a warp drive, and the visual effects of bending space are what you might expect things to look if NASA is successful with thier warp drive project - http://www.extremetech.com/extreme/164326-nasa-discusses-its-warp-drive-research-prepares-to-create-a-warp-bubble-in-the-lab The currently proposed spacecrafts to warp space have torus rings around them, just like the spacecraft in the vid. Also NASA has estimated with a warp drive compressing space in front of the craft and expanding it behind the craft we could travel to Alpha Centauri, the nearest solar system in 2 weeks to 2-3 months. So in all likelihood the space travelers in this film would come back from a successful trip relatively soon.

text: SO NOT IMPRESSED.      Jeez! Did Nolan stop smoking his cigar with his fellow gentlemen, to not realize his silly ideas in this film. Clearly, he is just another armchair philosopher. The characters look like they live in a very near future, BUT the technology being used to travel through black holes is not even close to reality.  2) Humanity is converging and things like stopping the population growth would be acted on way before there was no more food. Plus science will grow food way before humanity can travel long distances through space. Smh.  3) In the future when humanity might act on such a desperate decision, THEY as "we humanity" will not resemble a person today. author: luke wilson

text: Yet another silly Hollywood mess that demonstrates a complete ignorance of science and how it would be applied to avert crisis. Set to the tune of millions of wasted dollars.  If we run into the problem of critical food shortage, and we very well may, a more prudent solution would be to apply vertical farms. There are nations out there building them today. (Sadly, none of those nations are America.) We wouldn't wait until the problem has created a global dust-bowl dystopia then send a single crew to another planet. That solution, while it makes for pretty visuals and an entertaining, if silly story, is asinine.  I encourage people genuinely concerned with global food shortage to check out vertical farming, and particularly a book written by Mr. Diamandis and Mr. Kotler entitled: "Abundance".  I'll see this movie in theaters, but I'll bring my own grain of salt.

text: The worm hole as seen in this trailer is a depiction of Dr. Kip Thorne's theories of a spinning black hole. Kip is a world renowned Caltech Physicist and leader of wormhole theory. Nolan brought him on as an exec prod for the film and He is taking my breath away. Not only does he depict the most realistic future apocalypse with climate change destroying soil and producing dust bowls, but he is giving us a realistic glimpse into real theoretical interstellar travel. This man knows no equal when it comes to truly inspirational a moving tales. As was so eloquently said decade ago, he is "inspiring the imagination of a generation".

Worry, the fear of the possible, the unknown, the future: it may even be justifiable and a clear and present danger. But shift into faith gear, close your eyes and hear/see/feel JESUS … “I got this”. Smile it’s a done deal.

text: Looks like a a movie confronting issues of science and economics. The issues I can see on the trailer is earth is running out of food due to some natural or man made disaster involving massive dust storms similar to those of the Great Depression.  The line " the world doesn't need anymore engineers...... we ran out of food" is small reference to the fact that IRL the world is running out of farmers.  The government is sending people to other star systems to look for habitable worlds. I can see the use of hypersleep, some kind of space traveling device that bends space-time most likely an Alcubierre warp drive.  I'm excited to finally see a movie about the potential, adventure, and discoveries of the first interstellar travel by mankind. Something I feel is the most important issue for the future and survival of humanity.

text: Yeah... The plot/story sound kind of generic, but I'm sure that what we're seeing here is just 1/3. Nolan was quoted saying that with this one he is honoring 2001, this one looks more conventional than that but it's the director of Inception we're talking about (ability to take generic plot and inject interesting concepts and ideas into it). I know it's early but cinematography looks gorgeous, i was kind of skeptical since he's working with new DP in this one but Hoytema is more then a fine replacement, angles, colors... everything looks beautiful but let's not get ahead of our selves. I would love it if this is pretty much all the information we would get about this movie, i get that it's impossible since everyone depends on this one to be a hit (WB gave up two of their major franchise's just so they could get a cut of the cake, two major studios WB and Paramout are together in this, Legendary pic. bowed out of Man of Steel just so they can finance this one, how much this one earns will in my opinion define Nolan's future career since TDK films and Inception had all batman hype around it, if this one is indeed what Nolan claims it to be and is really that popular it would mean that Nolan is to stay and that more 'not so dumb but kind of emotionless' movies are on the way). I can't wait but I'm kind of afraid since the last time i had huge hopes for a Nolan movie i was kind of disappointed (The Dark Knight Rises... you can't really say it's his fault but Man of Steel too, and big time...)

text: Just some speculation:  "Anything that can happen, will happen." Murphy's law, definitely the main theme. Related to alternate realities, alternate versions of Earth. "I'm coming back." Wormholes connect two points in spacetime, which means that they would in principle allow travel in time, as well as in space. He's attempting to come back to Earth, but at another time. "I love you, forever." Emphasis on 'forever'. Silly observation, I know, but how will Matthew's character love his daughter forever?

text: I hate to be the bummer bunny here, but this is not an original concept by a long shot. Inception was, and as a result not much else mattered -- people were captivated.  This film doesn't have the same going for it. The concept has been done and done again. Rather than riding on a gimmick or original idea, this film's success rides on everything else: acting, screenplay, cinematography, etc.  It also helps that everyone thinks so highly of Nolan. If this were by another director most people would just yawn. I don't think it will be anything special, but it would be great to be proven wrong.

text: A film critique made a good point about Christopher Nolan's films. What Nolan does best is make films about complex subject matters and ideas, and make them appeal to a mass audience. So he adds the spectacle of the grand score, visuals and performances, but doesn't treat his audience like idiots. While we have films like Transformers 4 coming out which  looks like just a series of explosions, Nolan will probably give his audience something to engage their minds with. :)

text: Sure, brilliant idea Warner Bro's Studios! Lets just take planet Earth and do what we have always done with things we don't want: throw it away! Trash it! So we can move on to the next thing or planet in this case, and throw it away when the time comes too!  I don't think enough people understand just how valuable something like a planet like Earth is. Is it any small wonder we haven't found any other planets out there readily capable of supporting life? Planets like Earth may be the most valuable thing in the Universe! It literally mean the world to you, and me.  Ugh. The premise of this movie makes me sick.  Heads up though; we are indeed short on engineers, companies can't get enough of them! What we do have too much of though is PEOPLE and I don't think there will be an end to how much food we can salvage/produce.  Nonetheless this looks like an entertaining and interesting movie. Its just the idea's that its based on that makes me worry.

text: Interesting concept for interstellar travel!  But.....the earth will never run out of food.  I saw a lot of burning cornfields in this preview.  But.....there are other sources of food, both animal and vegetable.  Not all of the Entire World's food comes from midwestern cornfields!  If you live in a vacuum and have never travelled the world you might think that what Hollywood says could be accurate.  But it is not.  The whole premise behind Interstellar Travel should be to explore other worlds, gather resources, and build space-faring communities, not to escape the planet Earth.  If you were to dispose of the intriguing scenes where they are in space, what you are left with is a movie that sounds like the Kurt Russell flop: "Escape from L.A.", only on a global scale.  The Earth is beautiful my friends, and there are many many people who are actually succeeding at keeping it that way.

text: @The Ayala Factor Just to clarify, they're not going into a black hole, their space ship essentially creates a tiny one, or a singularity, to warp space-time, which allows for faster than light travel. Nothing could survive a black hole, nothing made of matter at least, the gravity of a black hole would rip the ship and its occupants apart down to the individual atoms. This movie is based on real scientific theory. And though some black hole theories account for the possibility of traveling vast distances of the universe if one went through it, all one has to do is account for the sheer gravitational power of the black hole beyond the event horizon to know that its just not possible. text: How is it that all you people cannot tell what the plot is? Is society really becoming that thick?!?! Have we now reached a point where if a movie or television show doesn't specifically spell every little tiny detail out for you...you miss the point...or think it sucks? I swear I am living through the movie "Idiocracy". The plot is simple and completely explained in the trailer. The Earth is going through an "end of days" type disaster where we can no longer grow food, our main character has seemingly wasted his life on becoming an engineer (since the world is ending who needs engineers), everybody in the world is attempting to figure out how to save the world, humanity finally makes the decision that we aren't supposed to save the world, we are supposed to leave this planet behind and explore the cosmos, to do this...humanity's last surviving scientists come together to solve the problem of interstellar travel (hence the name "INTERSTELLAR"). I got all of this from that one trailer as this is the first I have seen it, and I have not read anything about it. I can't wait to see how dumb this planet has become in 10 years time...

text: If the human species, or indeed any part of the biosphere, is to continue to survive, it must eventually leave the Earth and colonize space. For the simple fact of the matter is, the planet Earth is doomed... Let us follow many environmentalists and regard the Earth as Gaia, the mother of all life (which indeed she is). Gaia, like all mothers, is not immortal. She is going to die. But her line of descent might be immortal... Gaia's children might never die out--provided they move into space. The Earth should be regarded as the womb of life--but one cannot remain in the womb forever, Frank Tipler

In any case, we will have to leave this planet one day in the future if we are to survive as a species. As we speak the Andromeda galaxy is careening towards our Milky Way, asteroids pass within earths orbit constantly. We are always under threat of extinction. text: This is what I think the plot is:   Humanity faces extinction from starvation. The sun has become too unstable to sustain life on Earth for much longer. However, a wormhole has been discovered, and Earth's governments decide to send a team through the wormhole to discover where it leads to. If it is safe, humanity will begin a mass exodus through the wormhole.   The main character is an engineer and a pilot, which makes him suitable for such a mission. He has two children, a daughter and a son, which he loves very much. He leaves on the mission unwillingly, promising his children that he will come back.   However, years has passed. The main character's children has now grown up (Jessica Chastain plays his grown up daughter, note the similarity between the two) and Earth is in much more dire situation. The main character and his mission has not returned and the children starts looking for answers.

text: This movie is a more realistic take on SciFi and space travel, could be the launching point for a universe of it's own.  As much as I like to believe that the earth will one day become Star Fleet Headquarters, it's a bloody pipe dream. Reality of the fact is, if we don't poison and over populate this planet, it's only a matter of time a planetary catastrophe wipes us all out. I dig it. I've always been an avid believer, we need to start looking into leaving earth, ASAP. However that would take a global effort, and humans just aren't that sophisticated or educated yet. I wonder what triggers this mass project in the movie.  This seems like the movie I have been waiting for. Something to give the humans a reason to start looking up at the cosmos and embrace our destiny as explorers.

text: From what I gather, the story/plot is about a last-ditch effort to preserve the human race by using experimental space technology which does work in theory but, is currently still in the developmental stages by scientists.  First, in the preview there appears to be some sort of safe and advanced cryogenic-hibernation or stasis.  Secondly, Nuclear Fusion type rocket propulsion would be necessary to reach Saturn's orbit in a reasonable time-frame.  Lastly, this safe distance from the Earth would be required in order to activate the very first experimental Alcubierre drive which (in theory) creates a warp-bubble around a spacecraft allowing it to safely break the light-barrier and reach other solar systems.  I'm not an astrophysicist, I'm just desperate to leave this planet.

text: Did you know that 99% of the genetic information in you is not human? It's the genetic information of your symbiotic bacteria and virii, without which you could not survive. Now if a human was transported to the surface of a living alien world, and he was immersed in alien bacteria and virii, what would happen to him? Nothing good, I'll bet. On the other hand - even if we had the prerequisite technology for a manned interstellar expedition (we don't), such an expedition would require international co-operation, and it would be fantastically expensive. But to reduce carbon emissions to a point at which climate change would be stabilized would also require international co-operation, and it would be - much less expensive. Hmmm. So what, after all, is the point of this vile, vulgar and escapist tripe?

text: Two words, Time Dilation. We all know Chis  is fixated with time in his movies.  I'm a fan of him because of it.   Matthew's character tells the girl, I will be back. He will, but the uncertainty is if SHE (MANKIND) will be there when he returns.   If you talk about interstellar space travel, time dilation is the number one factor in planning for it. You can't get around it unless Eisenstein was wrong.   Unless its a wormhole. But that leaves more uncertainty because we're not sure what's on the otherside.of it. Matthew's character seems certain he is coming back, just not to what (state of the planet). We do know about Time Dilation though.  I hope someone tackles this in a plot if he didn't.

text: "We don't need engineers on Earth".  Seriously?  I totally want to see us go to space, but can we PLEASE stop this bull about the planet being a train wreck, and we have to get off the train?  Yes, I get that they want to have a 'compelling' reason to go to space, but what about doing it as a voyage of discovery?  Are we too cynical these days?  There are lots of good reasons to go to space that have nothing to do with the planet 'dying'.  Such as gathering resources (even in our own solar system); there are trillions of dollars worth of resources (various metals) in the form of asteroid mining, or Helium 3 extraction, etc.  That would create jobs, and do a hell of a lot for certain resource scarcities.

text: So far, the trailer has revealed quite a bit information.  First off in you see an Indian drone or UAV, this means that America is no longer the top dog anymore which is more likely the case in the future with the East being more dominate Russia, China or India.  This movie seems to cater to the masses that believe in global warming which can hamper current food supply which is a possibility.  Last we see the space tech which has been recently revealed by Nasa using warp drive based on a proven theory by a Mexican astrophysists.  We don't see no wormholes in this trailer, but we do see a ship with a mass ring around it and we also see a bubble that pulls, expands and decontracts the space around it.  Most likely its warp drive.  Also in the beginning you see the boy grown man, and later on in the trailer you see the girl in a red hair also grown wearing Matthews jacket.

text: the idea behind this film is simple, the ability to use a wormhole to jump to another planet and find a livable environment is perfectly plausible, though highly unlikely, and depending on the development of technology and the plausibility of being able to colonize mars and sustain that would not be plausible at all, we have technology to make that work for some time, but not for the 50+years this film is seeming to aim at. Interstellar travel is a fact of live and will happen eventually assuming our race evolves enough and the parameters of physics happen, due to the high likelihood that the ability of earth to sustain us as lifeforms will end. and while we may not know exactly how wormholes work in every facet, they do seem to be the best option in terms of interstellar travel out there due to the distances between solar systems being to great. this movie isn't silly, nor is it illogical based on the parameters it gives, its just exploring a thought path that we will probably explore one day. also as far as the food problem, that could very easily happen based on solar emission spectra changing in the slightest manner due to the core composition of our sun changing, so no it is not stupid, please stop talking as if you know everything in the field of astrophysics and biology, life isnt that simple.

text: I don't understand why people find it hard to believe the reasoning behind us being an interstellar traveling species.  During the existence of the Earth there have been over a handful of mass extinctions caused by different things.  We have the technology and the means to survive some things, but the odds are that we will eventually have to just leave the planet.    Let's say we find a way to prevent all those things, the sun is not going to last forever.  Perfecting interstellar travel is the only way we can truly survive as a species.  The ability to pick up our things and move to a different location is our only true means of survival, and you wouldn't want it to be the last thing you do before something catastrophic occurs.  Chances are, by then it is too late.

text: I don't exactly know why this trailer makes me cry. I know I am saddened by war, world hunger, political corruption, and social injustice; our current social ills, hollow innovations, mindless celebrity worship, superficial ambitions, and social superiority. Perhaps this trailer makes me believe that humanity is still destined for things greater than those which so morbidly depress me. Perhaps it makes me believe that the age of discovery is not over, that the true spark of innovation still exists somewhere, that there's still a sense of wonder to relished in our efforts. Perhaps this why i cry, out of hope.

text: If you use basic common sense they send a ship out to an already earth like planet..but on that ship will be some kind of matter transmitter so that they can transport the rest of humanity off our resource stripped earth..obviously we can't all fit in one spaceship no matter how big..the only way to travel from earth to the nearest habitable planet would be through that old staple of SF the portal or jumpgate..I'm guessing all this...but in most movie trailers its pretty easy to fill in the gaps....that's not to say that Mr Nolan won't do a great job of it and maybe we'll even get a couple of twists in there too..at least he tries to imbue his movies with slightly more intelligence than the SF clones that pass themselves off as entertainment these days...it'll be interesting for example ..the time delay between leaving earth and landing on the new home..is everybody back home still alive or have they left it too late?..I'm relying on Mr Nolan not to go cute and bring that sense of dark cynicism to this movie...cheers Prof Hugo Nebula PhD. Dr of Astrophysics at Jodrell Bank deep space telescope.

text: I love space movies, many of them are enthralling; I ardently respect all those astronauts who go to space and carry out experiments aboard the ISS. But, as a resident of this planet, I would love it if humanity would be less cruel to nature, and help maintain the balance of our ecosystem, by reducing pollution, violence, killing of animals. I am sure that no one will ever migrate to any other planet(Mars being the only option), because our body does not suit their atmosphere-if anyone goes on interplanetary travel, I am sure it will be a 1 way trip, and the whole world's population will never go, except astronauts & crazy billionaires. The Earth has life for a reason, no other planet has that, and we should be grateful for that. Wormholes are still a theory, but, if it is found to exist, interstellar travel will be carried out by astronauts only; 7 billion(who knows, 14 billion in the future) will never go and colonize on Alpha Beta whatever new planet that's discovered; we shall perish anyway due to geological events, maybe a massive earthquake, too much pollution, poisonous radiation from space etc. So, my point is, space travel should only be in fiction, novels and movies, and whatever NASA is doing, at least for now. It would be much useful for Earth & humanity's survival, if we concentrate on eradicating diseases, inventing a cure for all incurable diseases, reducing pollution of air/water/sound/land/electronic waste/radioactive waste etc., finding alternate ways of harnessing pollution free energy, letting animals live, and reducing violence, and lastly, doing all the mentioned work on a major scale(not like, only 20 cars run on electricity and the rest use gas) because, if the Earth survives, we do too-and the longer we live, the longer we can experiment on space travel. But Earth is our home and foundation, and we must not forget that.

text: The crew was killed, he never came back.  Well, that took 12 minutes to get to that point so this film will make more money per minute than any film before it.  Oh, the film is continuing?... it has them LIVE?!  WHAT!?  NO WAY!?  Oh look at all the pretty special effects.  Ok, let's have the IMPOSSIBLE happen because Kip Thorne wants to be known as an Imagineer like Einstein was, he wants his legacy to be that he imagined further than his knowledge should have allowed, he was a hero.  SO for that personal objective, we are now going to be fed a bag of worms about how people can survive going through a wormhole... oh great!  So first he tries to teach us that engineers are obsolete, then he tries to teach us that science built this thing!??  NOPE TO BOTH.  In the scenes they pull the power pack processing package from the Indian drone, as useful... oh wait, that's engineering.  Then they say we ran out of food, what... did engineering fail to come up with solutions?  NO WAY, engineers would have had people living where ever, with desalination wholesale, protected from radiation.  Listen, if engineering can build a star ship to go exploring to move MILLIONS of people off this planet, the same engineering would have built the systems to remake a new place to live on Earth, probably under the sea!  So this whole movie is based on... Kip Thorne playing around with his legacy.  So yeah, they all die and the movie ends after 12 minutes.  Let's all get refunds!!  hehe

text: I'm afraid this will be another disappointing sci-fi movie, like Gravity. It will probably be filled with all sorts of misconceptions about space, even though Kip Thorne has been the scientific consultant for it (and also executive producer). Remember the movie "Sunshine" from 2007? Brian Cox was the scientific consultant for that one, and yet the movie was filled with all sorts of misconceptions and inaccuracies that made me laugh. And what about Gravity? That unknown force that pulled Clooney away from the ISS was a total joke, same for the orbital nonsense between the Hubble, the ISS and the Russian satellites, etc.  Just so you know, Interstellar tells the story of a group of astronauts who "travel" through a black hole...with hopes of going somewhere else and then return to Earth, that is. For all science knows, the laws of physics break down inside a black hole due to the tremendous gravitational pull, that means that we can't possibly know, through physics, what happens exactly to things that cross the "event horizon" (that's the edge of the black hole, so to speak).  All science can tell for sure is that when something crosses the event horizon, there's no turning back, if you somehow managed to come out, it wouldn't be alive and in one piece. When Hawking talks about how it is possible for information to be preserved inside a black hole, it just means INFORMATION, in other words, the particles that form your body could still be "preserved" somehow but you would die nonetheless, all your atoms would be undone, and that isn't pretty. Whoever tells you that you can travel through black holes (survive the journey and come back to the same universe as if nothing happened, that is), doesn't have the math/mechanism to support this claim and Kip Thorne knows it. I bet all Kip has done is to help model the black hole, give direction to actors who will play scientist roles and perhaps a few more things, but I'm pretty sure this movie will still contain nonsense. Sci-fi directors usually claim they've made sure everything is scientifically accurate, showing us stuff like this>  Interstellar – Building A Black Hole – Official Warner Bros. so people can say "Oh! This time they've got it right!" when, in reality, only some things are accurate, the rest is usually nonsense. Movies like Sunshine and Gravity are clear examples of this. Curiously, there is a 1968 movie called "2001: A Space Odyssey" (perhaps you've heard about it, LOL) that gets most things right, without the need of using unlikely black hole travel, without the need to sell it for its "realism" or scientific accuracy, without flashy special effects, absurd amounts of money and without being too pretentious. The non-scientific parts of that movie are highly symbolic, which make it even better.  So Hollywood sci-fi movies nowadays have much larger budgets, a much higher availability of professionals from all branches, highly superior technology available, they generate much more money, etc. and yet they are worse every year... Why is that? I think it's because the essential guidelines of the business are wrong. They go for flashiness (big names, high numbers, extreme and flashy plots, etc.) instead of quality, they try to conciliate science with nonsensical extreme plots that are completely incompatible and absurd (my point being> don't try to sell the movie for its realism and accuracy if, in the end, it won't be so). This is the formula: big names + claims of scientific accuracy/realism + extreme plots filled with nonsense (the world is about to end, there's a critical accident/everything goes wrong, and the like) + stuff blowing up/getting destroyed + miraculous survivals + ultra hd cameras and all sorts of modern filters and effects + the hero saves the day (requiring his/her/their sacrifice, perhaps) = Next Hollywood sci-fi movie.

text: Smart, thrilling, exciting, imaginative and mind blowing movie with exceptional direction gorgeous cinematography, beautiful visuals, hard hitting sound effects, superb and powerful acting - it has it all. It is a great tribute to 2001: a space odyssey, it is a really challenging movie, it plays with your mind and imagination to the maximum degree.It is about love, hope, dreams, faith, family and evolution of humanity - not only in technological sense but in emotional sense as well. If you're sc-fi or movie fan in general you're going to be blown away and it is something to experience. Sure it has some logical issues and you have to suspend your disbelief but it is a rewarding movie and despite it being derivative, it is still unbelievable seeing the idea this big from someone's mind translated onto a big screen. 4.5/5

text: What an amazing movie! Well acted, well written and an amazing story/meaning. Nolan never fails to impress.  In advance. I want to say sorry for being THAT guy but I feel deeply offended by comments I see regarding religion :). If you are willing to listen to my opinion without spreading hate then click read more. I am happy to accept any of your RESPCTFUL arguments. :)         May I say that I do not study religion nor do I know a whole lot about others. I do however believe in God for various reasons. I am a Muslim so I am speaking in my religions point of view :). Many people may say that religion and science will never mix but I say and believe different. I would also like to clarify that there are also many things said in Islam (and other religions) that science cannot answer, therefore they are dismissed and considered inaccurate so I will not cover that (I'll leave it to the experts xD).   I just want to clear up that the Qur'an is historically proven to have been the oldest holy book that has been preserved and kept the same over 1400+ years (The time of it's revelation). What I'm saying here is that the Bible, Torah etc. were changed over time. That is a FACT.   Here is the most known example of science in the Qur'an. The birth of a human:   The miracle of man's creation is emphasised in many verses. Some of the information within these verses is so detailed that it was impossible for anyone living in the 7th century to have known it. Examples of these are as follows: 1. Man is not created from the entire semen, but only a very small portion of it (sperm). 2. It is the male that determines the sex of the baby. 3. The human embryo adheres to the mother's uterus like a leech. 4. The embryo develops in three dark regions in the uterus.   Let's pick out verses from the Qur'an that mention these.   1. Sperm undertake a journey into the mother's body until they reach the ovum. Only a thousand out of 250 million sperm succeed in reaching the ovum. At the end of this five-minute race, the ovum, half the size of a grain of salt, will let only one of the sperms in. That is, the substance of man is not the whole semen, but only a small part of it. This is explained in the Surat al-Qiyama as follows:   Does man reckon he will be left uncontrolled [without purpose]? Was he not once a drop of ejected semen? (Qur'an, 75:36-37)   2. Until fairly recently, it was thought that a baby's sex was determined by the mother's cells. Or at least, it was believed that the sex was determined by the male and female cells together. But, we are given different information in the Qur'an, where it is stated that masculinity or femininity is created out of "a drop of sperm which has been ejected."   He has created both sexes, male and female from a drop of semen which has been ejected. (Qur'an, 53:45-46)   Was he not a drop of ejaculated sperm, then a blood-clot which He created and shaped, making from it both sexes, male and female? (Qur'an, 75:37-39)   The developing disciplines of genetics and molecular biology have scientifically validated the accuracy of this information given by the Qur'an. It is now understood that sex is determined by the sperm cells from the male, and that the female has no role in this process.   The Qur'an even talks about the development of a foetus!   [We] then formed the drop into a clot and formed the clot into a lump and formed the lump into bones and clothed the bones in flesh; and then brought him into being as another creature. Blessed be Allah, the Best of Creators! (Qur'an, 23:14)   (All Information above is taken from http://miraclesofthequran.com/scientific_57.html)   Now to Stephen Hawking's theory.   In the Qur'an, which was revealed fourteen centuries ago at a time when the science of astronomy was still primitive, the expansion of the universe was described in the following terms:   And it is We Who have constructed the heaven with might, and verily, it is We Who are steadily expanding it. (Qur'an, 51:47)   The word "heaven," as stated in the verse above, is used in various places in the Qur'an. It is referring to space and the wider universe. Here again, the word is used with this meaning, stating that the universe "expands." The Arabic word "moosiaaoona" in the term "inna lamoosiaaoona," translated into English as "it is We Who are steadily expanding it", comes from the verb "evsea," meaning "to expand." The prefix "la" emphasises the following name or title and adds a sense of "to a great extent." This expression therefore means "We expand the sky or the universe to a great extent." This is the very conclusion that science has reached today.   All this was known to Muhammad (Peace be upon him) 15 hundred years ago! All things we have recently discovered.   Please take in mind that I am 13 (14 soon) I am not just a Muslim because I was born into it. I am a Muslim because I believe what it teaches is right! Not the BS you see in the media (ISIS, Al Qaeda etc.)   I would also like to say that I respect all of your opinions and I thank you for listening to mine :)   Have a great day!

text: Here's my take. A valiant attempt to take on a big block buster sci-fi movie about quantum physics and deep human themes of love and humanity. However, I think Nolan bit off more than he could chew with this one. After viewing, I kept thinking this film was over indulgent in nearly every way. The characters were weak, plot rushed (terrible flow), overly melodramatic, and ultimately disappointing in its scope. What he lacked in those key areas he tried to make up with state of the art special effects and a suffocation of scientific information (there's nothing wrong with that in general but it's just foolish to try and cram that level of cosmology and quantum physics education into a 3 hour mainstream movie). To me, Nolan is like the Starbucks of film making; on the surface his style and choice of themes seem intellectual and authentic. However, under that surface is just a watered down, massed produced corporate product under the guise of quality. I don't think this is a masterpiece in the same way "2001" or "Alien" were. Just like the album "The Wall" by Pink Floyd or the film "Apocalypse Now" by Francis Ford Coppola, this movie aimed way too high without hitting the mark.

text: As a kid I use to read the short stories by science fiction greats Issac Asimov, Arthur C. Clarke and others. I use to read a lot about Albert Einstein and his many theories and see if I could prove the ones he missed. I use to think my grandfather's workshop must have been what Einstein's laboratory must have looked like as I was amazed at the things my grandfather could do. This is a movie that I think they would all love. This is a movie I have been waiting a long time for!  Throughout the film my wife was constantly amazed as to how I knew what was about to happen as though I had already seen the movie which I swear I hadn't. I highly recommend this movie!   Do not go gentle into that good night, Old age should burn and rave at close of day; Rage, rage against the dying of the light.  Though wise men at their end know dark is right, Because their words had forked no lightning they Do not go gentle into that good night.  Good men, the last wave by, crying how bright Their frail deeds might have danced in a green bay, Rage, rage against the dying of the light.  Wild men who caught and sang the sun in flight, And learn, too late, they grieved it on its way, Do not go gentle into that good night.  Grave men, near death, who see with blinding sight Blind eyes could blaze like meteors and be gay, Rage, rage against the dying of the light.  And you, my father, there on the sad height, Curse, bless, me now with your fierce tears, I pray. Do not go gentle into that good night. Rage, rage against the dying of the light.  Dylan Thomas, 1914 - 1953

text: I say, a very interesting idea (which reveals itsef by the end of the movie..) around which they built a very unlikely scenario, almost ridiculous : am I the only one who noticed that a former engineer working as a farmer for about 10 years goes from one day to another, without any training, health or psychological control WHATSOEVER goes on a NASA spacecraft as main pilot.. As the last chance to save humanity.. Come on.. And all that on a secret base located in corn fields a few dozen miles from his house.. Kiss my back.. That main actor whatever his name had a bad play (maybe because of film director..) he looks and sounds more like a spoiled Hollywood actor than as an engineer hahah)) And all crew keep saying thick trivialities about theory of relativity.. For the spectator to grasp.. All the while they penetrate wormholes and black holes.. Actually - but that's something else - black wholes actually crush whole galaxies with such gravity power that even light gets trapped in.. Means probably a human spacecraft blows to dust way before it approaches its "horizon". Real, funny movie, interesting scenario, good esthetics, but quite too dumb to make a 2001 Odyssey II..

text: Extraordinary movie, please read 1. Elegant universe by Brain greene 2. Brief history of time by Stephen hawking and if you have lot of time like me 3. On nature of space time (Elegant universe on Steroids) by Brian greene, maybe White light ( for Tiplers paradise and 5 dimensional beings), then proceed to watch this movie.... I keep pondering on the myriad of themes and stunning visual, the Black hole, Millers planet, Manns planet, the Tesseract, Bulk beings... I was sorry they did not show Edmund's planet (at all).  One clarification for viewers,Cooper is trapped in Tesseract which is a 5 dimensional space,(Tiper's Paradise) this allows him to be in all time in all places simultaneously,he can choose where he wants to see(??how) but cannot communicate because he is beyond event horizon of a black hole. In the end he can leave the tesseract and enter a universe that is ready to receive him (maybe created for him at the instant of collapse of tesseract).  Only one plot loop hole, if Copper has travelled all the way to 120years and Quantum gravity has been discovered, why any one has not gone to Edmund's planet till this day??
